# DEFRA Accessibility Standards

## ‚ôø WCAG 2.1 COMPLIANCE

### Compliance Requirements
- ALWAYS meet WCAG 2.1 Level A (minimum)
- ALWAYS meet WCAG 2.1 Level AA (required)
- STRIVE for Level AAA where possible
- ALWAYS test with real users
- ALWAYS document accessibility features
- NEVER compromise on accessibility

### Four Principles of Accessibility
1. **Perceivable**: Information must be presentable in ways users can perceive
2. **Operable**: Interface components must be operable
3. **Understandable**: Information and UI operation must be understandable
4. **Robust**: Content must be robust enough for various assistive technologies

## üé® VISUAL DESIGN

### Color and Contrast
- ALWAYS maintain WCAG AA contrast ratios:
  - Normal text: 4.5:1 minimum
  - Large text: 3:1 minimum
  - UI components: 3:1 minimum
- NEVER rely on color alone to convey information
- ALWAYS provide additional visual cues
- ALWAYS test with color blindness simulators
- ALWAYS support high contrast modes

### Typography
- ALWAYS use readable fonts
- MINIMUM font size: 14px (desktop), 16px (mobile)
- ALWAYS allow text resizing up to 200%
- ALWAYS maintain readable line spacing (1.5x)
- ALWAYS limit line length (80 characters max)
- NEVER use justified text alignment

## ‚å®Ô∏è KEYBOARD NAVIGATION

### Keyboard Support
- ALWAYS ensure full keyboard accessibility
- ALWAYS provide visible focus indicators
- ALWAYS implement logical tab order
- ALWAYS support keyboard shortcuts
- NEVER create keyboard traps
- ALWAYS test without a mouse

### Focus Management
- ALWAYS show clear focus indicators
- ALWAYS manage focus programmatically when needed
- ALWAYS return focus after modal closes
- ALWAYS skip to main content link
- NEVER remove focus outlines without replacement
- ALWAYS test tab order thoroughly

## üñºÔ∏è IMAGES & MEDIA

### Alternative Text
- ALWAYS provide alt text for informative images
- ALWAYS use empty alt="" for decorative images
- ALWAYS describe image purpose, not appearance
- ALWAYS include text in images as alt text
- NEVER use "image of" or "picture of"
- ALWAYS make complex images accessible

### Multimedia Content
- ALWAYS provide captions for videos
- ALWAYS include audio descriptions
- ALWAYS offer transcripts
- ALWAYS provide controls for auto-playing content
- NEVER auto-play with sound
- ALWAYS allow pause/stop/hide for moving content

## üìã FORMS & INPUTS

### Form Accessibility
- ALWAYS associate labels with inputs
- ALWAYS group related fields
- ALWAYS provide clear instructions
- ALWAYS indicate required fields
- ALWAYS show inline error messages
- NEVER rely on placeholder text alone

### Error Handling
- ALWAYS identify errors clearly
- ALWAYS describe how to fix errors
- ALWAYS preserve user input
- ALWAYS announce errors to screen readers
- NEVER use color alone for errors
- ALWAYS validate accessibly

## üîä SCREEN READER SUPPORT

### ARIA Implementation
- ALWAYS use semantic HTML first
- ONLY use ARIA when necessary
- ALWAYS follow ARIA authoring practices
- ALWAYS test with screen readers
- NEVER change native semantics unnecessarily
- ALWAYS ensure ARIA labels are meaningful

### Screen Reader Testing
Test with:
- NVDA (Windows)
- JAWS (Windows)
- VoiceOver (macOS/iOS)
- TalkBack (Android)
- Always announce important changes
- Never create invisible content barriers

